class Solution {
    public int minimumArrayLength(int[] nums) {
        int m = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int x : nums) {
            m = Math.min(m, x);
        }

        int cnt = 0;
        for (int x : nums) {
            if (x == m) {
                cnt++;
            }
        }
        return cnt;
    }
}

This solution calculates the minimum value in the array and then counts the number of times this minimum value occurs in the array. The length of the array after all operations are performed is then returned as the result. The reason the remaining array always has the same length after performing the operations is because each operation is removing the minimum value and adding a number that is a result of the modulo operation, thus, the array length remains the same. The only change is that some elements in the array might have changed their values.

